classified as \u003Cstrong\u003Esynovial joints\u003C/strong\u003E. These joints are characterised by a joint cavity filled with synovial fluid, which allows for smooth gliding movements between the carpal bones. This type of joint is essential for the flexibility and range of motion in the wrist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECartilaginous joints\u003C/strong\u003E - These joints are connected entirely by cartilage and do not have a synovial cavity\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHinge joints\u003C/strong\u003E - These allow movement in one plane, like the elbow\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPivot joints\u003C/strong\u003E - These allow rotational movement around a single axis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBall and socket joints\u003C/strong\u003E - These allow movement in multiple planes, like the shoulder\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intercarpal joints are classified as synovial joints, which allow for a range of movements.","Synovial joints are characterised by a joint cavity filled with synovial fluid, providing lubrication and reducing friction.","Intercarpal joints specifically allow for gliding movements between the carpal bones."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 J